People who smoke are at a higher risk of losing their teeth.
Smoking damages not only the lungs, but also the teeth - a long-term study by Potsdam suggests this.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk drops quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is evident from the long-term study of an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutritional Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers were at risk of losing their teeth prematurely, 2.5 to 3.6 times higher.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth decay are caries and inflammation of the gums, emphasizes the DIfE.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
The link between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum inflammation in smokers.
It is unclear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
People who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take over ten years for the risk to fall back to the level of non-smokers, said first author Thomas Dietrich of the University of Birmingham.
One has to convince people to become non-smokers, said study leader Heiner Boeing of the DIfE: "Smoking shortens the lifespan."
Not smoking is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health until old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 are affected by toothlessness, the DIFE reported.
Previous studies have already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study supports the findings.
