Pound rises due to accelerated wage growth in the UK
The pound rose sharply following data showing an increase in wage growth in the United Kingdom, while the FTSE 100 was boosted by the SABMiller bid target.
Between May and July, earnings without bonuses in the United Kingdom grew by 2.9% compared to the same period of the previous year.
This percentage was the quickest and most accurate estimate of the timing of an interest rate increase since 2009.
The pound rose by more than 1% against the dollar to $1.5505 and climbed to 0.84% against the euro to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.3730.
The FTSE 100 index closed with an increase of 1.49% to 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the outstanding stock on the market and made a 20% jump after taking over offer from rival AB InBev.
A transaction would combine the two largest breweries in the world and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were 0.9% higher, according to encouraging news from the luxury goods competitor Richemont.
Richemont’s latest sales figures beat all expectations and also showed that sales in China – a key market for Burberry – are reporting growth again.
Shares of Glencore rose 5% after the mining giant said it took in $2.5 billion through a share sale as part of its debt reduction strategy.
The shares of the packaging and paper group Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, down 4.3% after Goldman Sachs set its rating for the company to "sell".
JD Sports rose 3.1% after the sports apparel company reported a pre-tax earnings of 46.6 million for the half-year.
The head of JD Sports says higher wages are jeopardizing the expansion.
JD Sports CEO Peter Cowgill says a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean “more purchasing power in the pockets of potential customers.”
But it is unlikely that this purchasing power will offset the higher labor costs at his company, he says.
The costs could hit JD Sports’ expansion plans, he added, and that could mean fewer additional jobs.
