Metcash launches ground-level campaign to combat Aldi infestation
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA branches from an Aldi advance in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground-breaking campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGAaide brand through mainstream marketing and marketing via social media shows.
IGA dealers and suppliers are jumping on board, with brands such as ice cream maker Simmo from Dunsborough distributing samples in IGA stores and shop owners selling discounted tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29 as the food, alcohol and appliances wholesaler conducts its annual investor strategy day.
Much is at stake as South Australia and Western Australia make up nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that 12 months after the opening of its first markets, Aldi will grab about five percent of the food market in these two states and take away sales from all existing players, but mostly independent retailers.
According to a report published this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in annual sales and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 branches in SA next year and 30 in WA and will achieve sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and food business and in the quantities on Metcash’s high fixed-cost base could cost Metcash about $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash’s food and beverage sales to drop 3.8 percent in 2016, 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and reduce its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, top fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr Douglass’ comments.
But it is assumed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenue from Metcash’s food and food trade, which supplies approximately 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting the operational debt reduction while simultaneously pressuring sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler resists and invests more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products every week and to improve IGA retailers in improving their stores by growing faster fresh foods and delivering a better selection of private label foods.
Metcash’s chief executive, Ian Morrice, says the price adjustments and store remediation programs will increase at Elan and hopes the wholesaler will return to profitable growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis to be backed by Australian Tennis Association President Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damages" in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to Australian Tennis Association President Steve Healy, deserves more praise than criticism for his own behavior.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, who is repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks", came into the spotlight due to Kyrgios' notorious confrontation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated by the referee twice, with Harrison exclaiming, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the child."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis bat after a spasm thwarted a potential U.S. open victory by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was staunchly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
"One thing that I'm pretty excited about is the fact that in my opinion, Thanasi was a little drawn into the fight," Healy said.
He broke a bat when he lost to a spasm in the U.S. Open, but he’s not the first player to break a bat out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he’s not proud of it.
But, really, he has behaved extremely well in the US Open, even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he was treated a little too harshly.
He is a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he is respected in the dressing area, he trains hard, he is well in shape, he is a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be served on his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to take Kyrgios into account in the important pre-decision that begins on Friday, and he describes the "common decision" as the right one for everyone, but he also assures the Canberra man to return to the team as a long-term fixture."
"First of all, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversies around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I think Nick has made the ascent very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out best. He is rising in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions and keep it out of time.
Europe’s refugee crisis: Hungary declares a state of emergency, closes the border, detains refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and blocked the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday and detained all those who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man’s-land and Serbian officials reacted indignantly.
The people who had fled violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
Frustrations have risen.
When a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants chanted “Open the border!” and shouted insults at the Hungarian Bereitschaftspolizei.
Some rejected food and water from protest.
Serbia’s foreign minister said it was “unacceptable” that migrants would be sent back from Hungary as more and more arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
There must be talks with Brussels and other countries in the coming days," said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turbulence on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc failed to agree on a common immigration policy at a contentious meeting in Brussels.
The ministers, however, agreed to share responsibility for the 40,000 people who sought refuge in overcrowded Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that the EU states would take another 120,000 refugees, including some from abroad.
Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special summit of the European Union to discuss the continent’s immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not place its hopes on an early action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The emergency in two southern regions on Tuesday gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis, allowing them to block roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country is also planning to build a barbed-wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it ended a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prisoners were used in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a significant bottleneck and entry point into the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted, however, that most arriving economic refugees are looking for a better life, not war refugees who are entitled to protection – a view that strongly contradicts other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence that the government built along the southern border with Serbia a crime, which also imposes higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
"Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government declares a state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament still has to agree to the deployment of the military, which is expected next week, but Associated Press reporters have been seeing heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, Orban’s national security adviser, said authorities managed to reach 45 people while trying to cross the border, while 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a barbed-wire train wagon arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process the data of people and pressed a crowd to push themselves there.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway connection between Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
Election 2016: Hillary Clinton's lead over Bernie Sanders in national poll halved
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a two-digit lead in the Democratic race for nomination at the national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders wins over her on the ground.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primary (58 percent previously), while Sanders is in second place, with 27 percent (up 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he will run for president, receives the support of 15 percent of the Democratic primary voters.
More than five months before the start of the pre-elections, most democratic voters say it is too early to say that their opinion determines which candidates they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more consistent in their election than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders has made some gains.
Clinton holds a large lead in women and moderates, but these lead have decreased.
Their support for the men has dropped significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind.
Clinton’s advantage among democratic voters under the age of 50 has vanished, and she and Sanders are now on an equal footing.
Clinton, however, still has a big lead among the older voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a two-digit lead in the Liberals, but Sanders now has a 5-point lead in this group.
About half of Democratic voters nationwide say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations and another 15 percent would only support her because she is the candidate.
Six percent would not support it.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton’s current supporters are especially enthusiastic about her.
The views are more mixed among those who currently don’t support Clinton — only about a quarter would enthusiastically support her.
While 48 percent of Democratic primary voters say they support Clinton enthusiastically, fewer Republican voters say this about their top candidate Donald Trump (35%).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the view that it’s time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she is the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton’s supporters also mention her connection to Bill Clinton (9 percent).
Consent to deal with the problems and selectability are also cited.
As the vice president throws a potential for the presidential office into the balance, 57 percent of Democratic voters in the pre-election vote want to see him in the race – even though a third believe he shouldn’t.
When Democratic voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the top.
Of Clinton’s supporters, more than half say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton’s lead over Sanders increases from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chance of winning the election; however, that number has dropped by 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far a second in this measurement, but the percentage that sees him as the "most selectable" has risen.
Nevertheless, when asked what is more important to a candidate, Democratic voters call questions about electability.
Just like last month, no single Democratic candidate or potential candidate stands out as unacceptable for these primary voters.
The Democratic candidates or potential candidates produce good results in some important characteristics among voters of their party’s pre-elections.
Majorities consider Clinton, Sanders and Biden to be honest and trustworthy and endowed with strong leadership qualities.
Biden is best off in honesty among the three candidates, while Clinton’s strength is in leadership.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters do not believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent have no opinion on him.
Democratic voters of the pre-elections generally also see Clinton, Sanders and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
With all these measurements, about a quarter of democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions continue to be asked about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and a server during her tenure as Secretary of State, most Democratic voters in the pre-election are satisfied with her statement of the matter and say it has not affected their views at all.
But it’s a different story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on this matter was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no impact on their general views on Clinton, although 36 percent said their views on her had deteriorated further.
It’s mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views have gotten worse by Clinton.
Although Clinton is seen by her party’s voters as honest and trustworthy, this remains a problem for her among registered voters overall: only 32 percent see them as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month and 15 points less since May.
62% of voters do not consider them to be honest and trustworthy.
At the same time, 55 percent of voters nationwide view Trump as not honest and not trustworthy.
Clinton and Trump, however, get good marks in leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush cut off best in honesty.
A majority sees Sanders more as honest, but like Carson, many have no opinion of him.
The error rate for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the preliminary elections is 6 percentage points.
Ben Carson comes close to Donald Trump in nationwide poll
Ben Carson is close behind Donald Trump in the latest CBS News/New York Times poll
The two candidates have now lost half of the voter support in the new poll, and others are dramatically losing ground.
Republican voters continue to support Trump in large numbers nationwide, growing from 23% in the last CBS poll conducted ahead of last month’s Fox News debate, to 27% in Tuesday’s poll.
But Carson shot from 6% to 23% in the same period.
The survey also found that Carson is doing well with demographic groups and outperforms Trump among Republican voters with college education.
The rest of the field, with the exception of Carly Fiorina and Ohio Governor John Kasich, has been beaten down by Wisconsin Governor Scott Walker, who fell the lowest from 10% support last month to now 2%.
Former Florida Governor Jeb Bush, former Arkansas Governor Mike Huckabee and Florida Senator Marco Rubio are in third place with 6%.
The margin of error for the sample of 376 people from Republican voters in this latest poll is plus or minus 6% and was conducted in September.
The latest CNN/ORC poll released last week shows that Carson is rising in polls — he lands at 19% support among Republicans, behind Trump with 32% support.
