Five members of the fraternity charged with the death of a Baruch college newcomer
Nearly two years after a student died during a tedious ritual of a student union in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are filed against five people.
Members of the New York Baruch College Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013 and delayed his transportation to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he was blindfolded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand, and repeatedly attacked as he tried to approach a target via a frozen field.
Mr. Deng eventually complained of headaches, then he fell unconscious.
The members of the Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng became powerless and reportedly waited an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change Deng’s clothes, google his symptoms and contact Andy Meng, the national president of the fraternity, for advice, police chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
"At this point, the members began to hide utensils and basically put the welfare of the brotherhood above that of Michael Deng," said Chief of Police Wagner.
He could not be revived, and he died the next morning of his injuries.
After an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly inflicted with blunt force injuries to the head, torso and thighs.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the Brotherhood's bullies; at least one student dies from the bullies every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Fraternities and their members must be held accountable, and this step by authorities is very important.
A County Grand Jury of Monroe recommended an indictment for third-degree murder of the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr. Meng, are also charged with harassing attacks and forming a criminal association.
“We want to hold not only the people involved accountable, but if there is an organization that has sanctioned this – officially or unofficially – we will hold them accountable,” Wagner said at a press conference on Tuesday.
Baruch College has banned fraternity, and the national fraternity has revoked its membership in the local group.
This will happen if the Fed raises interest rates.
An interest rate hike is coming, and the rise will waver, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slip into a recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long it will last and how long it will last.
In particular, history offers little guidance for the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
Therefore, representatives of the U.S. Central Bank have so strongly emphasized that investors should not focus on when they start raising interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that the whole excitement about an interest rate increase may have been exaggerated.
"The Fed's first rise since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of 'cheap money,'" Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal highs, but still at too low a level to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here is a historical trend-based look at how some areas of the economy might react:
As the market saw last month, anticipating interest rate increases can make things volatile for a while.
As soon as the increase occurs, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There appears to be a tendency for asset yields to be squandered 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the delay in monetary policy,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after Fed interest rate increases.
More precisely, the market has been mostly on the upward trend in the past 35 years - about 14 percent - on the way to raising interest rates, rather flat in the 250 days after that (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the past six cycles.
Deutsche Bank said that the effects on the shares tend to occur later in the growth cycle and the return begins to decrease.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and could accelerate a recession.
It is extremely noteworthy here that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point when the Fed raises interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 have only doubled nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was at 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes on such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky and raise the question of “whether it’s different this time around,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been focused all year on an interest rate hike by the Fed, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, all of the increase cycles from 1950 to today took place in a super cycle with increasing momentum in GDP and pre-recession heights very quickly overshadowed by the onset of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is clearly a slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and these are 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase, and the pattern is quite similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic course.
In the case of bonds, the yields seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to shrink closer and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-interest bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, although “we are still cautious about expecting higher returns,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones thinks that the markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have expanded, and volatility has risen – all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
On the whole, companies that do most of their business in the U.S. will benefit if interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debts will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market and also the financing of their debts.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks tend to react very positively three months after an initial interest rate increase,” Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report to customers.
Firms with a strong balance sheet averaged 5 percentage points higher than those with a weak balance sheet after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital yields and low volatility in their shares also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points).
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see gains from higher returns, even if experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
