At their most anticipated meeting this year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras Mahagoni table to decide if it’s time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threatening them at one end of the decorated, two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests ahead of all other things.
The central bank has a two-fold mandate from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, the Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict, and it will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to be weaned from the unprecedented incentive by the near-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
Although most of the economic data shows that it is growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed representatives to amplify this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds – even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing they observe,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is justification enough to continue to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is insecure for the financial market.
About half of the economists polled by Bloomberg recently predicted an interest rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of an increase.
This suggests a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate, unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that a further increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that the Fed’s policy will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed would raise rates at this point,” he said.
If she does, “she would have to go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that raising interest rates would calm the financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the Fed would trade.
Even a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the recovery in the US.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that she expected an increase in the rate this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market this year was solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed sees as full employment.
Salary increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was consistently below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, Fed officials said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of the strain on the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world slumped at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16% below its peak in May, as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would thwart global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the May high.
For the Fed representatives, market turbulence influences the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks had not occurred, they would be taking the toll at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, Senior Research Fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the U.S. Federal Reserve.
Now he predicts that they will wait at least a month to get the effects better under control.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The central bank’s influence has been enormous in recent years.
The mere indication by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “close” its monetary expansion triggered confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of Envestnet Inc.’s global asset management strategy.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, remarked this month that "the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements seemingly unrelated to the economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee who advocates an interest rate increase, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions “despite limited discernible impacts on growth in the United States,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed representatives reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The latest turbulences are not coming close to this plane, he said.
“She certainly doesn’t want to get into the situation where she’s afraid of an interest rate hike because the markets get excited,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don’t think it should be ahead of time.
