Poison control centers in the U.S. report a nearly 400 percent increase in the number of children under the age of twelve who ingest heavily alcoholic hand sanitizers, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, cases of hand sanitizer intakes in children under the age of 12, reported by poison control centers, rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children are increasingly coming to these products, and unfortunately a percentage of them end up going into the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children drink disinfectants intentionally, while some do it to impress their friends or because of a test of courage on social media.
Videos on YouTube show how teens drink disinfectants just because of a cheap experience.
Teenagers have allegedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children can be attracted by attractive scents of disinfectants.
“A child doesn’t think this is bad for it,” Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand sanitizers) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scent, which are very appealing for children.
Hand sanitizers contain between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, few syringes can lead to alcohol poisoning.
“It’s highly concentrated alcohol,” said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Toxic Emergency Call Center at the University of Kansas Hospital, to Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So, you wouldn’t let a sip of whisky go around, but people leave these hand sanitizers within reach of children, and if children come up with it, then it’s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four syringes of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179, twice the threshold legally considered drunk in an adult, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside of Atlanta.
Nhaijah muttered her words and was unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children’s hospital for signs of brain trauma as the girl had fallen through the alcohol and bumped her head, Ritchey said.
“That was very scary,” Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah’s mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal for my child.
Lopez has recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic products or disinfectants and store hand sanitizers outside the child’s reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants were associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand sanitizers containing a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect that the product contained methanol, a deadly solution, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as an active substance.
