According to the German government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the transformation of the car.
The Federal Cabinet decided on Wednesday a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the outskirts of the IAA Motor Show of a "new era of mobility".
Automated and networked driving will increase road safety and reduce congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who will also meet with representatives of industry at the IAA.
The strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid transition to digital listening radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being built on Highway 9 in Bavaria.
In order to ensure that the driver is "not burdened with additional liability risks", the federal government wants to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the maximum permissible speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
The federal government also wants to push for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
With automated driving, the car increasingly takes over the lead, the driver becomes more and more a passenger.
The technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economic Affairs, highly automated driving on highways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads "only to be expected far after 2020".
The value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the site in Germany is estimated by the authors of the study for 2025 to be around 8.4 billion euros.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said Sören Bartol, a SPD transport politician.
However, the issue of liability in case of accidents and the security of the personal data of the drivers must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans still see self-driving cars skeptical - much more than French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the test organization Dekra, presented at the AA on Wednesday, concludes that only 8% of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32% expect only in 20 years, 31% do not believe in it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, while in the US, 33 percent.
Nevertheless, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to give up control during the entire journey on all roads.
