EU wants to double mercury limit in robbery fishery
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, giving consumers a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticized the plans: "Risks and side effects of wrong industrial and environmental policies are passed on with full weight to pregnant women and toddlers," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the nerve agent limits for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, should be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily loaded with mercury that, based on the limits still in force, about 50 percent of the catches may not be sold.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unsold.
In return for this relaxation, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram, according to Foodwatch.
However, Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller fried fish, such as carp, are usually so low-loaded that they already meet the planned maximum values today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious diversionary manoeuvre that alone helps the economy," Wolfschmidt said.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal for humans, which is highly enriched across the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The Federal Government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn babies".
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment declares on its homepage with regard to the current maximum values that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through coal combustion.
German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written information from the Federal Ministry of the Environment to the Greens-Bundestag MP Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube, was "permanently and comprehensively exceeded", the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.quecksilber-aktion.foodwatch.de
